Gaussian Process Emulation of FPSO motion simulators

Lachlan Astfalck

January 04, 2019

This document demonstrates the research presented in Chapter 4. First, a synthetic dataset is generated, then demonstration of the emulation methodology is presented, finally the diagnostics for the results are given.

Generation of synthetic dataset

As the original dataset used within the research is confidential, the methodologies presented are demonstrated herein using a synthetic dataset. The dataset is generated so as to be similar to the original data, albeit in a smaller dimensional space. This is to reduce the computational demands in the emulator training for the point of this tutorial. It is straightforward to extend this code incorporate higher dimensions, more input data, and variations of linear-circular inputs.

First we select the number of training and validation points, and number of dimensions that we wish to build the emulator in.

N <- 500
N_predict <- 500
N_total <- N + N_predict
dim <- 5

Then, a random Latin hypercube sample of length N_total is generated over a \(dim\)-dimensional hypercube from the package lhs. Note that unlike the original research, this process does not induce any correlations or dependencies in the synthesised data.

X_LHS <- maximinLHS(N_total, dim)

N points are randomly sampled from the Latin hypercube sample. These points act as the training data, and the remainder act as validation points.

sample_index <- sample(seq(1, N_total, 1), N, replace = FALSE)

X_train <- X_LHS[sample_index, ]
X_predict <- X_LHS[-sample_index, ]

X_all <- rbind(X_train, X_predict)

The Latin hypercube generates \(d\)-dimensional points in \([0,1]^d\). To demonstrate the developments presented in the research, 2 of the input dimensions are redefined on a circular domain with the dimensions scaled to \([0,2\pi]\). We do this by specifying a vector defining the type of input along each dimension (this seems odd, but becomes useful later), and multiplying the circular dimensions by \(2\pi\).

types <- c("circular", "circular", "linear", "linear", "linear")
circ_index <- which(types == "circular")

X_all[ ,circ_index] <- X_all[ ,circ_index] * 2 * pi

Hyper-parameter values are now specified in the vector hp_true. Random values have been chosen. Next, a list of distance matrices is calculated. dist.circular() from the package circular is used to calculate the distance matrix of the circular parameters. The covariance matrices for each dimension are easily calculated from the distance matrix, and the final covariance matrix is calculated as an element-wise product of each of the separate covariance matrices.

Possibly add some math into here from the paper

hp_true <- c(6.5, 7.5, 2, 3, 1, 1, 0.005)

SE <- function(d,alpha,rho) {
  alpha * exp(-d^2/(2*rho))
}

C4_Wend <- function(d,tau) {
  (1 + tau * d/pi + (tau^2 - 1)/3 * (d^2)/(pi^2)) * pmax((1 - d/pi)^tau, 0)
}

d <- list()
K_ind_true <- list()
for (i in 1:length(types)) {
    if(types[i] == "circular") {
        options(warn = -1)
        d[[i]] <- as.matrix(dist.circular(X_all[ ,i], method = "geodesic"))
        K_ind_true[[i]] <- C4_Wend(d[[i]], hp_true[i])
        options(warn = 0)
    } else {
        d[[i]] <- as.matrix(dist(X_all[ ,i]))
        K_ind_true[[i]] <- SE(d[[i]], 1, hp_true[i])
    }
}

K_all_true <- matrix(hp_true[dim+1], N_total, N_total)
for (i in 1:dim) {K_all_true <- K_all_true * K_ind_true[[i]]}
K_all_true <- K_all_true + diag(hp_true[dim+2], N_total, N_total)

Finally, we generate our synthetic data by drawing a single sample from a zero-mean multivariate-normal distribution with K_all_true set as the variance-covariance matrix.

y_synth <- as.matrix(rmvnorm(1,rep(0,N_total),K_all_true))
y_samples <- y_synth[1, 1:N]
y_predict <- y_synth[1, (N+1):(N_total)]

Emulation methodology

This section is presented in two parts: the first focuses on the estimation of the hyper-parameter values, and the second on the prediction of the validation data.

Finding maximum-a-posteriori estimates of hyperparameters

To estimate the hyper-parameter values, we solve for the values that maximise the posterior:

Add math from the text in here, actually figure out the posterior

Note that this is a simplification of Equation A.4.7 for the case when the mean function \(H\beta\) is not considered. The posterior is expressed as a proportionality as the constants will not affect the optimisation routine. The function log_posterior takes a vector of hyperparameters, a list of distance matrices, the observed values, and the types vector as an argument and return the log posterior. The function optimx from the package optimx is then used to solve for the values of hp that maximise the function log_posterior.

Taking the exponential of the parameters given to optimx allows for optimx to search over \(\mathcal{R}^d\) for parameter values, and then constrains them to be positive (and \(\geq 6\) for the circular parameters).

log_posterior <- function(hp, d_xx, y_samples, types){

  circ_index <- which(types == "circular")
  hp[circ_index] <- exp(hp[circ_index]) + 6
  hp[-circ_index] <- exp(hp[-circ_index])
  
  k_xx_sample <- list()
  for (i in 1:length(types)) {
    if(types[i] == "circular") {
        options(warn = -1)
        k_xx_sample[[i]] <- C4_Wend(d_xx[[i]], hp[i])
        options(warn = 0)
    } else {
        k_xx_sample[[i]] <- SE(d_xx[[i]], 1, hp[i])
    }
  }
  
  k_dim <- dim(k_xx_sample[[1]])[1]
  k_xx_all <- matrix(hp[length(types)+1], k_dim, k_dim)
  for (i in 1:length(k_xx_sample)) {k_xx_all <- k_xx_all * k_xx_sample[[i]]}
  k_xx_all <- k_xx_all + diag(hp_true[length(types)+2], k_dim, k_dim)


    dlike <- dmvnorm(y_samples, rep(0,k_dim[1]), k_xx_all, log = TRUE)
    return(-dlike)

}

d_xx <- lapply(d, function(x) x[c(1:N), c(1:N)])

hp_optim = optimx(par = log(c(0.5, 1.5, 2, 3, 1, 1, 0.005)), 
                                    fn = log_posterior, 
                                    method = "Nelder-Mead", 
                                    d_xx = d_xx, 
                                    y_samples = y_samples, 
                                    types = types)

hp_MAP <- exp(coef(hp_optim))
hp_MAP[circ_index] <- hp_MAP[circ_index] + 6
print(hp_MAP)
##                  p1       p2       p3       p4        p5        p6
## Nelder-Mead 6.63838 8.021369 2.161145 6.931255 0.8564401 0.9374952
##                      p7
## Nelder-Mead 0.008116238

The resulting hyper-parameters are close to the initial values. Note that GPs with enough training data are remarkably robust to error in the hyper parameters.

Predicting using the emulator

First the covariance variance matrix is partitioned into \(K\), \(K_{*}\), and \(K_{**}\), and \(K^{-1}\) and \((\text{Cholesky}({K}))^{-1}\) are pre-calculated. The estimated parameter values are used for this, and not the assumed values.

K_ind_MAP <- list()
for (i in 1:length(types)) {
    if(types[i] == "circular") {
        options(warn = -1)
        K_ind_MAP[[i]] <- C4_Wend(d[[i]], hp_MAP[i])
        options(warn = 0)
    } else {
        K_ind_MAP[[i]] <- SE(d[[i]], 1, hp_MAP[i])
    }
}

K_all_MAP <- matrix(hp_MAP[length(types)+1], N_total, N_total)
for (i in 1:dim) {K_all_MAP <- K_all_MAP * K_ind_MAP[[i]]}
K_all_MAP <- K_all_MAP + diag(hp_MAP[length(types)+2], N_total, N_total)

k_xx <- K_all_MAP[c(1:N), c(1:N)]
k_xxs <- K_all_MAP[c(1:N), c((N+1):(N_total))]
k_xsxs <- K_all_MAP[c((N+1):(N_total)), c((N+1):(N_total))]
k_xx_inv <- solve(k_xx)
k_xx_chol <- solve(t(chol(k_xx)))

The predictive mean and covariance are calculated from Equations 5.A.4 and 5.A.5 in the dissertation, or A.4 and A.5 in the original publication.

M <- t(k_xxs) %*% k_xx_inv %*% as.matrix(y_samples)
Cov <- k_xsxs - crossprod(k_xx_chol %*% k_xxs)

This gives the mean function and the variance-covariance matrix for the validation points, trained from the training data. To estimate the validation data we make 1000 random draws from a multivariate normal distribution with mean M and variance-covariance matrix Cov.

y_draw <- as.matrix(rmvnorm(1000, mean = M, sigma = Cov))

y_draw now contains \(1000 \times 500\) matrix with columns \(i\) providing 1000 draws from the distribution of the \(i\)th predictive point in y_predict. We now use these estimates, and the real values of y_predict to diagnose the performance of the emulator.

Diagnostics

Finally we produce the diagnostic plots included in the paper. The functions to produce these plots are included at the bottom of the document.

p1 <- var_scatter(y_draw, 0.1 * var(y_samples))
p2 <- coverage_plot(y_draw, y_predict)
p3 <- IPE_plot(y_draw, y_predict)
p4 <- var_density(y_draw, 0.1 * var(y_samples))
p5 <- IPE_density(y_draw, y_predict)
p6 <- cred_intervals(y_draw, y_predict)

grobs <- list(p1, p2, p3, p4, p5, p6)
lay <- rbind(c(1,4,2),
             c(3,5,6))
grid.arrange(grobs = grobs, layout_matrix = lay)

var_scatter <- function(y_draw, var_accept) {

    df <- data.frame(index = seq(1,length(y_draw[1,]),1))
    df[ ,2] <- apply(y_draw, 2, var)

    ggplot(df, aes(df[ ,1], df[ ,2])) + 
        geom_point(shape = 4, alpha = 0.7) +
        geom_hline(yintercept = var_accept , linetype = 2) + 
        xlab("Point Index") +
        ylab("Variance") +
        ggtitle("Variances") +
        theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), 
                    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), 
                    aspect.ratio = 1)

}


coverage <- function(samples, y_actual) {

    coverage <- data.frame(actual = seq(0,0.99,0.01))

    for (k in 1:100) {

        upper <-  apply(samples, 2, quantile, 0.50 + k/200)
        lower <-  apply(samples, 2, quantile, 0.50 - k/200)

        in_quantile <- 0

        for (m in 1:length(samples[1, ])) {
          if (y_actual[m] < upper[m] & y_actual[m] > lower[m]) {
            in_quantile <- in_quantile + 1
          }  
        }

        coverage[k,2] <- in_quantile/length(samples[1, ])

    }

    return(coverage)

}

coverage_plot <- function(samples, y_actual) {

    cov <- coverage(samples, y_actual)

    ggplot(data = cov) +
            geom_line(aes_string(x = colnames(cov)[1], y = colnames(cov)[1])) +
            geom_point(aes_string(x = colnames(cov)[1], y = colnames(cov)[2])) +
            theme_bw() +
            xlab("Nominal Coverage") +
            ylab("Empirical Coverage") +
            ggtitle("Coverage Plot") +
            coord_fixed(ratio = 1) +
            theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), 
                        panel.grid.minor = element_blank())

}


IPE_plot <- function(samples, y_actual) {

    IPE <- data.frame(index = seq(1,length(y_actual),1))
    E <- apply(samples, 2, mean)
    V <- apply(samples, 2, var)
    IPE[ ,2] <- (y_actual - E) / sqrt(V)

    ggplot(data = IPE) +
        geom_point(aes_string(x = colnames(IPE)[1], 
                                                    y = colnames(IPE)[2]), 
                                                    shape = 4) +
        geom_hline(yintercept = -3, linetype = 2) + 
        geom_hline(yintercept = 0) + 
        geom_hline(yintercept = 3, linetype = 2) +
        theme_bw() +
        ylim(-6,6) +
        xlab("Point Index") +
        ylab("Individual Prediction Error") +
        ggtitle("Individual Prediction Errors") +
        theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), 
                    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), 
                    aspect.ratio = 1)

}


var_density <- function(y_draw, var_accept) {

    V <- data.frame(var = apply(y_draw, 2, var))

    ggplot(V) + 
        geom_density(aes(x = var)) +
        geom_vline(xintercept = var_accept , linetype = 2) + 
        xlab("Prediction Variance") +
        ylab("Density") +
        ggtitle("Prediction Variance Density") +
        theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), 
                    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), 
                    aspect.ratio = 1)

}


IPE_density <- function(samples,y_actual) {

    IPE <- data.frame(index = seq(1,length(y_actual),1))
    E <- apply(samples, 2, mean)
    V <- apply(samples, 2, var)
    IPE[ ,2] <- (y_actual - E) / sqrt(V)

    ggplot() + 
        geom_density(data = IPE, aes_string(x = colnames(IPE)[2])) +
        geom_line(data = data.frame(x = seq(-6,6,0.01), 
                                                                den = dnorm(seq(-6,6,0.01))), 
                            aes(x,den), 
                            linetype = 2, 
                            color = "#8b8b8b") +
        xlim(-6,6) +
        xlab("Individual Prediction Error") +
        ylab("Density") +
        ggtitle("Individual Prediction Error Density") +
        theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), 
                    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), 
                    aspect.ratio = 1)

}


cred_intervals <- function(y_draw, y_predict){

    df <- data.frame(index = seq(1,length(y_draw[1,]),1))
    df[ ,2] <- apply(y_draw, 2, var)

    output_percentile <- data.frame(y = y_predict, 
        quantiles = t(apply(y_draw, 2, quantile, probs = c(0.025,0.25,0.50,0.75,0.975))))

    ggplot(output_percentile, aes(x = y)) +   
        geom_boxplot(aes(ymin = quantiles.25., 
                                         lower = quantiles.25., 
                                         middle = quantiles.50., 
                                         upper = quantiles.75., 
                                         ymax = quantiles.75.), 
                                 stat = "identity", 
                                 alpha = 0.15) +
        geom_point(aes(x = y, y = quantiles.50.), size = 0.2) +
        geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1) +
        xlab("Ariane7 Output") +
        ylab("Emulator Prediction") +
        ggtitle("Emulator Credible Intervals") +
        coord_fixed(ratio = 1) +
        theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), 
                    panel.grid.minor = element_blank())

}
